{{Infobox scientist | name = Michael John Denton | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1943|8|25}} | residence = [[Australia]] | citizenship = British/Australian | fields = [[Medicine]], [[Biochemistry]] | institutions = Centre Hospitalier de l’Université de Monréal, Canada <!---| workplaces = ---> | alma_mater = [[King's College London]] <!--- | doctoral_advisor = | known_for = | awards = ---> | website = }}
'''Michael John Denton''' (born 25 August 1943) is a [[United Kingdom|British]]-[[Australian]] author and biochemist. He is a Senior Fellow at the Discovery Institute's Center for Science and Culture. Denton’s most prominent book, ''[[Evolution: A Theory in Crisis]]'', inspired [[intelligent design]] proponents Phillip Johnson and Michael Behe.<ref>http://www.discovery.org/p/521</ref>
==Biography== Denton gained a medical degree from [[Bristol University]] in 1969 and a [[PhD]] in biochemistry from [[King's College London]] in 1974. He was a senior research fellow in the Biochemistry Department at the [[University of Otago]], [[Dunedin]], [[New Zealand]] from 1990 to 2005. He later became a scientific researcher in the field of genetic eye diseases. He has spoken worldwide on [[genetics]], [[evolution]] and the anthropic argument for design. Denton's current interests include defending the "anti-Darwinian evolutionary position" and the design hypothesis formulated in his book ''Nature’s Destiny''.<ref>[http://www.michaeljdenton.com/?p=5 Background of Denton and his scientific work] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120304125001/http://www.michaeljdenton.com/?p=5 |date=March 4, 2012 }}</ref> Denton describes himself as an [[agnostic]].<ref name=Agnostic1>{{cite book|title=Signature in the Cell|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=laW5vuTLNXEC&pg=PA556 |author=Stephen C. Meyer|quote=Michael Denton, an agnostic, argues for intelligent design in Evolution: A Theory in Crisis, 326–43.|publisher=[[Harper Collins]]|accessdate=13 November 2010}}</ref><ref name=Agnostic2>{{cite book|title=Evolution, Creationism, and Intelligent Design |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=o-c1IZtSnoIC&pg=PA291 |author=Tom Frame|quote=Michael Denton, Darwin and Intelligent Design In contrast to the other would-be pioneers of intelligent design, Denton describes himself as an agnostic, and his book was released by a secular publishing house.|accessdate=13 November 2010}}</ref> He is currently a senior fellow at the [[Discovery Institute]]'s [[Center for Science and Culture]].
==Books==
===''Evolution: A Theory in Crisis''=== {{See also|Evolution: A Theory in Crisis}}
In 1985 Denton wrote the book ''Evolution: A Theory in Crisis'', presenting a systematic critique of [[neo-Darwinism]] ranging from [[paleontology]], [[fossils]], [[homology (biology)|homology]], [[molecular biology]], [[genetics]] and [[biochemistry]], and argued that evidence of design exists in nature. Some of book reviews criticized his arguments.<ref>Mark I. Vuletic. [http://www.talkorigins.org/faqs/denton.html "Review of Michael Denton's Evolution: A Theory in Crisis"], The Talk Origins Archive</ref> He describes himself as an [[evolutionist]] and he has rejected biblical [[creationism]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=NKZeO1H9fh8C&pg=PA155&dq=michael+denton+evolutionist&hl=en&ei=mcrNTYLQCoyu8QP_8Nj9DQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=book-preview-link&resnum=7&ved=0CFsQuwUwBg#v=onepage&q=michael%20denton%20evolutionist "Profile in Evolution and creationism in the public schools by Angus Macleod Gunn"]</ref> The book influenced both [[Phillip E. Johnson]], the father of intelligent design, Michael Behe, a proponent of irreducible complexity,<ref>{{cite web|title=Intelligent Design Video: 'Unlocking the Mystery of Life'|url=http://evomech1.blogspot.com/2007/01/intelligent-design-video-unlocking.html|website=Evolution Research - General Evolution News|accessdate=28 March 2015}}</ref> and [[George Gilder]], co-founder of the [[Discovery Institute]], the hub of the [[intelligent design movement]].<ref>Forrest and Gross(2004) pp 17, 259</ref> Since writing the book Denton has changed many of his views on evolution, however he still believes that the existence of life is a matter of design.<ref>[http://www.michaeljdenton.com/?p=1 My Biological World View] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110529165507/http://www.michaeljdenton.com/?p=1 |date=May 29, 2011 }}</ref>
===''Nature's Destiny''=== Denton still accepts design and embraces a non-Darwinian evolutionary theory. He denies that randomness accounts for the [[biology]] of [[organisms]]; he has proposed an evolutionary theory which is a "directed evolution" in his book ''Nature's Destiny'' (1998). Life, according to Denton, did not exist until the initial conditions of the universe were fine-tuned (see [[Fine-tuned Universe]]).<ref>Allene Phy-Olsen, Evolution, Creationism, and Intelligent Design, 2010, p.72</ref> Denton was influenced by [[Lawrence Joseph Henderson]] (1878-1942), [[Paul Davies]] and [[John D. Barrow]] who argued for an [[anthropic principle]] in the cosmos (Denton 1998, v, Denton 2005). His second book ''Nature's Destiny'' (1998)<ref>[http://www.talkorigins.org/faqs/comdesc/camp.html 29+ Evidences for Macroevolution: A Response to Ashby Camp's "Critique"], [[Talk.Origins]] "Interestingly, it appears that Denton has finally rectified his misunderstanding about nested hierarchies and common descent, since in his latest book he unconditionally assumes the validity of the nested hierarchy, common descent, and the tree of life."</ref> is his biological contribution to the anthropic principle debate, dominated by physicists. He argues for a law-like evolutionary unfolding of life.<ref>"[T]he second argument, developed in Part 2, that the cosmos is fit also for the evolutionary development of life" (p. xiv). See also especially chapter 12.</ref>
==Publications== * ''[[Evolution: A Theory in Crisis]]''. Adler & Adler, 1985. {{ISBN|0-917561-52-X}} * ''Nature's Destiny: How the Laws of Biology Reveal Purpose in the Universe'', New York: Free Press, 1998. {{ISBN|0-7432-3762-5}} * ''Evolution: Still a Theory in Crisis''. Seattle, Washington: Discovery Institute, 2016. Paperback: {{ISBN|978-1936599325}}
